WEBVTT

00:00:00.400 --> 00:00:05.200
Hi everyone, my name is Max Patterson and I'm a data scientist at Suffolk Construction.

00:00:06.080 --> 00:00:11.120
Today, I'm excited to share with you how we leverage the Posit suite of tools to streamline

00:00:11.120 --> 00:00:16.879
and productionize our machine learning workflows. Specifically, I'll be detailing the workflow for

00:00:16.879 --> 00:00:23.600
one of our models that focuses on enhancing project safety. I'll be covering several key

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:29.200
areas in today's presentation. First, I'll introduce Suffolk as a company, giving you

00:00:29.200 --> 00:00:35.040
a better understanding of our perspective. Next, I'll detail the purpose and significance of our

00:00:35.040 --> 00:00:41.119
safety model, explaining why it's crucial for our operations. Following that, I'll walk you

00:00:41.119 --> 00:00:45.520
through the key information about the model itself and the objectives we aim to achieve

00:00:45.520 --> 00:00:51.119
through its implementation. We will then discuss the critical events in the model's workflow

00:00:51.119 --> 00:00:54.959
and how we utilize the Posit suite to accomplish these tasks efficiently.

00:00:55.919 --> 00:00:59.759
Additionally, I'll demonstrate some of the outputs from this process,

00:00:59.759 --> 00:01:03.599
including a Shiny dashboard and an automated email reporting system.

00:01:04.639 --> 00:01:09.760
Finally, I'll touch on data security and how Posit enables us to implement row-level

00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:14.400
permissioning within our deployed applications, ensuring that our data remains secure and

00:01:14.400 --> 00:01:23.360
accessible only to authorized users. So, who is Suffolk? Suffolk Construction is a leading

00:01:23.360 --> 00:01:29.440
general contractor headquartered in Roxbury, Massachusetts, just south of Boston. We have a

00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:36.320
strong presence across the United States with offices in New York, Florida, Texas, California,

00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:43.919
and several other states. Our work spans multiple sectors, including commercial, gaming, aviation,

00:01:43.919 --> 00:01:51.440
healthcare, life sciences, education, and mission critical. With a workforce of approximately 3,000

00:01:51.440 --> 00:01:57.199
employees, Suffolk is recognized as one of the 25 largest general contractors in the United States.

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:04.080
As a general contractor, safety is of paramount importance to us.

00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:09.759
Our commitment to safety is reflected in our jobsite signs that remind everyone that the

00:02:09.759 --> 00:02:15.679
most important thing they do each day is to go home to their families. To ensure the highest

00:02:15.679 --> 00:02:20.800
standards of safety, we track various key performance indicators related to safety

00:02:20.800 --> 00:02:26.960
performance. One of the industry standard metrics we use is the Total Recordable Incident Rate,

00:02:26.960 --> 00:02:32.960
TRIR, which measures the number of incidents as a function of the total number of hours worked on

00:02:32.960 --> 00:02:40.240
the jobsite. At Suffolk, we monitor this metric at the project, regional, and company levels.

00:02:41.199 --> 00:02:45.360
While TRIR is an excellent metric for assessing historical performance,

00:02:45.919 --> 00:02:51.520
it is inherently a lagging indicator. This limitation inspired us to develop our safety

00:02:51.520 --> 00:02:56.880
model, which aims to assess project risk proactively rather than retrospectively.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:03.119
By providing forward-looking risk assessments, our project teams can better prepare for potential

00:03:03.119 --> 00:03:07.039
risks and implement strategies to mitigate incidents before they occur.

00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:15.360
The first generation of our safety model was developed several years ago by a third-party

00:03:15.360 --> 00:03:21.279
vendor. However, a couple of years ago, we decided to bring the model in-house and replicate the

00:03:21.279 --> 00:03:28.160
third-party model as closely as possible. Recently, with the availability of newer data streams over

00:03:28.160 --> 00:03:33.440
an extended period, we revamped the model to include additional features that enhance risk

00:03:33.440 --> 00:03:39.360
assessment. Based on feedback from our teams, we determined that distributing project risk

00:03:39.360 --> 00:03:45.199
assessments on a weekly basis would be most effective. So, we run the model on a weekly

00:03:45.199 --> 00:03:51.360
cadence, incorporating data related to staffing, trade partners, who are our subcontractors,

00:03:52.479 --> 00:03:58.720
observations, which are inspections conducted by our staff, incident history, project schedule

00:03:58.720 --> 00:04:04.160
details, and core project information. To disseminate the model's findings,

00:04:04.160 --> 00:04:06.960
we developed a Shiny app for visualizing the results,

00:04:07.520 --> 00:04:11.919
and we use Cordo to send automated email reports highlighting key projects.

00:04:15.440 --> 00:04:20.320
The workflow for our safety model is fairly standard and can be divided into two distinct

00:04:20.320 --> 00:04:27.440
processes, model training and model inference. Both processes utilize an ODBC connection to

00:04:27.440 --> 00:04:33.440
Databricks, which is our data warehouse. We employ the POSIT suite of tools to train and deploy the

00:04:33.440 --> 00:04:40.880
model. Once deployed, we can make API calls to the model for inference. We perform batch inference

00:04:40.880 --> 00:04:46.079
every week using a script that gathers data from our Databricks tables, creates the model input,

00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:52.079
makes a request to the model's API endpoint, and writes the predictions back to Databricks in a

00:04:52.079 --> 00:04:58.239
table. Once this process is complete, our Shiny app displays the most recent predictions,

00:04:58.799 --> 00:05:04.640
allowing end users to access the data. Additionally, any projects identified as high

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:10.160
risk are highlighted in an emailed report, which includes insights from the model explaining why

00:05:10.160 --> 00:05:17.920
the project is considered high risk. The POSIT suite offers a comprehensive set of tools that

00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:24.320
allow us to productionize our model workflow. The TidyModels library enables us to train

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:31.600
multiple models and select the best one based on hyperparameter tuning. The DBI library allows us

00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:37.440
to establish an ODBC connection to Databricks, enabling us to read data and write predictions

00:05:37.440 --> 00:05:43.279
back to the database. This connection also supports row-level permissioning in Databricks,

00:05:43.279 --> 00:05:49.119
ensuring that data access is restricted based on predefined permissions, thereby relieving

00:05:49.119 --> 00:05:56.000
data scientists from managing data access. Vetiver allows us to version our models easily

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:00.000
and deploy them to POSIT Connect, where they can be served as API endpoints.

00:06:01.040 --> 00:06:07.679
Quarto helps us schedule the model workflow and send out key results via email. Finally,

00:06:07.679 --> 00:06:13.359
we use a Shiny app to present the model results in a user-friendly format for our stakeholders,

00:06:13.359 --> 00:06:15.519
with the app also deployed to POSIT Connect.

00:06:18.640 --> 00:06:22.160
In this section, I will walk you through the script we use to train our data.

00:06:23.040 --> 00:06:27.040
While I have a separate script dedicated to generating the training data,

00:06:27.040 --> 00:06:32.160
I will not be showcasing that script or the actual data set used for this public demonstration.

00:06:32.880 --> 00:06:38.559
However, this provides an excellent opportunity to highlight the utility of the PINS library,

00:06:38.559 --> 00:06:43.119
which allows us to save a version data set and access it from a separate script.

00:06:43.760 --> 00:06:46.720
This is precisely what I am doing here in this cell.

00:06:50.160 --> 00:06:55.359
One of the standout features of the TidyModels library is its comprehensive suite of tools

00:06:55.359 --> 00:06:59.679
for model training. I will guide you through some of the key features we utilize.

00:07:01.040 --> 00:07:05.679
Initially, we generate our train-test split to evaluate the model's performance

00:07:05.679 --> 00:07:09.359
on an independent data set that the model has not encountered before.

00:07:13.920 --> 00:07:19.040
Here, we introduce the concept of a model recipe, which I believe is an unsung hero

00:07:19.040 --> 00:07:25.760
of the TidyModels process. Incorporating a model recipe is advantageous because it enables data

00:07:25.760 --> 00:07:31.279
transformations within the model workflow itself, thereby minimizing the preprocessing

00:07:31.279 --> 00:07:35.440
required before feeding data into the model when it is served as an API.

00:07:36.880 --> 00:07:42.160
In our script, we flag the project number and week columns as IDs, ensuring that the

00:07:42.720 --> 00:07:47.440
columns are included in the model workflow but not used as features.

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:54.720
The HadIncident column, which indicates whether an incident occurred, is assigned the outcome

00:07:54.720 --> 00:07:59.279
role, signaling to the model that this is the target variable we aim to predict.

00:08:00.399 --> 00:08:06.720
We also handle missing values by removing any rows with NA values for numeric features,

00:08:06.720 --> 00:08:09.440
and perform one-hot encoding for nominal features.

00:08:10.399 --> 00:08:14.320
It's important to note that unless the one-hot parameter is set to true,

00:08:14.959 --> 00:08:19.839
the encoding will create N-1 features for N values in a nominal column.

00:08:22.320 --> 00:08:26.720
Additionally, we create interaction terms between specific features

00:08:26.720 --> 00:08:30.959
and perform downsampling to address the imbalance in our training data set.

00:08:31.760 --> 00:08:36.719
This imbalance, characterized by a higher number of project weeks without incidents

00:08:36.799 --> 00:08:43.039
compared to those with incidents, is obviously favorable from a business and safety perspective,

00:08:43.039 --> 00:08:45.440
because it means that incidents are relatively rare.

00:08:46.239 --> 00:08:51.039
However, without downsampling, the model would suffer from poor recall,

00:08:51.039 --> 00:08:55.440
struggling to correctly identify project weeks with incidents in the testing set.

00:08:58.239 --> 00:09:04.159
We specify two models for training, a random forest classifier and an XGBoost classifier.

00:09:05.119 --> 00:09:09.919
To optimize the models, we use the tune function to specify hyperparameters,

00:09:09.919 --> 00:09:11.919
which we define shortly later in the script.

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:18.559
A notable feature of TidyModels workflows is the ability to train multiple models

00:09:18.559 --> 00:09:23.280
using multiple recipes within the same process by using the workflow set function.

00:09:25.119 --> 00:09:30.000
This allows us to test the performance of various recipes on each specified model

00:09:30.159 --> 00:09:35.760
and select the best one. Although we are using a single recipe in this demonstration,

00:09:35.760 --> 00:09:38.719
it's worth mentioning the flexibility this feature provides.

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:45.760
We define our k-fold cross-validation strategy for training

00:09:45.760 --> 00:09:48.640
and specify the range of hyperparameters to test.

00:09:51.119 --> 00:09:57.119
For each hyperparameter, we test five different values evenly distributed across the specified

00:09:57.119 --> 00:10:05.760
range. During the training process, we track performance metrics such as precision,

00:10:05.760 --> 00:10:08.880
accuracy, recall, and area under the curve.

00:10:12.799 --> 00:10:16.719
The workflow map function integrates all the components of our script,

00:10:16.719 --> 00:10:20.239
including the workflow set, cross-validation specification,

00:10:20.880 --> 00:10:23.840
hyperparameter tuning grid, and performance metrics.

00:10:24.799 --> 00:10:27.359
Running this function initiates the training process.

00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:34.000
Based on our previous evaluations, we know that the random forest

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:39.200
model outperforms the XGBoost model, so we will skip the step of comparing their performance.

00:10:39.840 --> 00:10:43.919
However, examining the training metrics allows us to assess the model's performance.

00:10:44.559 --> 00:10:50.000
Julia Silgi has published numerous insightful blog posts on iteratively tuning model hyperparameters,

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.479
which I highly recommend for those starting from scratch.

00:10:53.440 --> 00:10:57.760
For the sake of brevity, I know that the model performed best as a random forest,

00:10:57.760 --> 00:11:02.159
so we will assume that the best model is the random forest model and proceed.

00:11:05.440 --> 00:11:10.559
In this cell, I extract the best random forest model based on my choice of metric,

00:11:10.559 --> 00:11:12.880
in this case, the area under the curve metric.

